### Step 2: The baseline results (Clean network)
> *"On a clean local network, we got very interesting results. Both **Zenoh** and **gRPC** performed incredibly well, with baseline round-trip latencies under **2.5 milliseconds** (with Zenoh at ~1.0 ms and gRPC at ~2.2 ms).*
> 
> *However, **MQTT** had a baseline latency of **46 milliseconds** even with zero network delay. I investigated this and found it's a client-side library bottleneck: the Paho-MQTT python client loop uses a default select-polling timeout of 50ms, which artificially delays packet processing. This shows that the choice of client library is just as important as the wire protocol itself."*

---

### Step 3: Good 5G scaling (Nominal conditions)
> *"Under normal 5G conditions—where we injected 20ms one-way delay, representing a 40ms physical RTT limit—both **Zenoh and gRPC scaled beautifully**.*
> 
> *Even when we scaled to 10 concurrent devices at a 10Hz message rate, both Zenoh and gRPC maintained stable round-trip times right at the network floor of **~43 milliseconds** (with p95 tail latencies under 46ms). MQTT's latency was stable but higher, around **84 milliseconds**."*

---

### Step 4: Degraded 5G scaling (The big finding)
> *"The most critical finding came when we tested degraded network conditions (80ms one-way delay, representing 160ms RTT, and 1% packet loss) under high load (10 devices, 2KB payloads, 10Hz rate).*
> 
> * **gRPC and Zenoh** absorbed the packet loss successfully. Their median latency stayed right at the network floor of **~164 milliseconds**, and their worst-case p99 latency stayed under **450 milliseconds** due to standard TCP retransmissions.
> * **MQTT completely collapsed**. Its median latency jumped to **31.9 seconds**, and its p95 tail latency exploded to **58.3 seconds**. 
> 
> *This is a classic case of **Buffer Bloat**. Because MQTT relies on a central broker, a single packet loss blocks the TCP socket queue. As the edge server kept pushing messages at 10Hz, packets queued up inside the broker's buffer waiting for TCP retransmissions, creating an endless backlog."*

